In acidic electrolytes, the high mobility of protons leads to low concentration of adsorbed hydroxyl species on the catalyst surface. O2 molecules are chemisorbed on the catalyst surface, then getting electrons from the electrode. This mechanism is called the inner-Helmholtz plane (IHP) process (shown in Fig. 3b). Therefore, the catalysts used for acidic H2O2 production are conductors, which can facilitate O2 chemisorption and electrons transfer. This mechanism elaborates that noble metal-based catalysts and the emerging M–N–C catalysts with high ORR activity can be used for H2O2 production in acidic electrolyte. The elemental steps for acidic H2O2 production are:3O2→O2,ads\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
